# Report on the Rising Cost of Gas: Causes and Analysis

The cost of gas has been rising significantly in recent years, impacting consumers globally and influencing economic activities. Understanding the multifaceted reasons behind this increase requires an examination of supply and demand dynamics, geopolitical factors, production constraints, market speculation, and policy decisions. This report presents a comprehensive and detailed analysis of the causes driving the rising gas prices, supported by data and expert insights from trusted sources.

## Supply and Demand Imbalance

The primary driver of rising gas prices is the imbalance between supply and demand. Global demand for natural gas and crude oil has been recovering strongly following the COVID-19 pandemic downturn, but supply has struggled to keep pace.

### Demand Recovery and Growth

After a 4% drop in natural gas demand in 2020 due to the pandemic, demand has rebounded and is expected to grow at an average annual rate of approximately 1.5% from 2019 to 2025 ([IEA, 2021](https://www.iea.org/reports/gas-2020/2021-2025-rebound-and-beyond)). This growth is driven by economic rebounds in emerging markets and a return to near pre-pandemic consumption levels in mature markets. Industrial use accounts for about 40% of gas demand growth, with power generation and transport sectors also contributing significantly.

However, the pandemic has caused a permanent loss of about 75 billion cubic meters (bcm) of natural gas demand growth over the forecast period, indicating a structural shift in consumption patterns ([IEA, 2021](https://www.iea.org/reports/gas-2020/2021-2025-rebound-and-beyond)).

### Supply Constraints

On the supply side, natural gas production is expected to rise incrementally until 2025, with a significant jump anticipated around that year. However, the current period is marked by limited new supply entering the market, contributing to tightness and price volatility ([CNBC, 2021](https://www.cnbc.com/2021/10/28/energy-crisis-analysts-split-on-whether-gas-prices-will-remain-high.html)).

Key supply challenges include:

- **US Shale Industry Vulnerability:** The US shale sector, a major driver of recent global gas output growth, faces reduced upstream investment, with spending on shale tight oil and gas declining by 50% year-over-year in 2020 ([IEA, 2021](https://www.iea.org/reports/gas-2020/2021-2025-rebound-and-beyond)). This limits the sector's ability to replace declining conventional production and meet LNG export demands.
- **Geopolitical Risks in the Middle East:** Production growth in the Middle East depends on large conventional projects in countries like Saudi Arabia, Iran, and Qatar. However, oil price volatility and political uncertainties pose downside risks to supply stability ([IEA, 2021](https://www.iea.org/reports/gas-2020/2021-2025-rebound-and-beyond)).
- **Low Investment Due to Past Price Trends:** Prolonged periods of low crude oil and gas prices in the previous decade discouraged investment in new drilling and infrastructure, leading to constrained supply capacity today ([Natural Gas Costs Rising, 2021](https://www.cfu.net/news/newsletter/november-2021/why-are-natural-gas-costs-rising)).

