## Geopolitical and Political Factors

Geopolitical tensions and political decisions significantly influence gas and oil prices by affecting supply routes, production decisions, and market confidence.

### Middle East Instability and Shipping Routes

The Middle East remains a critical region for global oil and gas supplies. Political turmoil, conflicts, or threats to key shipping chokepoints such as the Strait of Hormuz and the Suez Canal can disrupt supply chains, leading to price spikes ([IG UK, 2018](https://www.ig.com/uk/news-and-trade-ideas/commodities-news/how-can-political-events-affect-the-oil-price--42098-180209)).

For example, the Iranian threat to block the Strait of Hormuz in 2011-2012 caused significant market anxiety despite no actual blockade occurring. Such political posturing can cause speculative price increases and supply concerns.

### OPEC Production Decisions

The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), controlling over 50% of global oil production, wields considerable influence over prices. Decisions by OPEC to limit or increase production affect global supply levels. Recently, OPEC and its allies have been reluctant to increase production despite rising demand, contributing to the supply-demand imbalance ([Essaytown, 2011](https://www.essaytown.com/subjects/paper/rising-gas-prices/49595)).

### US Political and Policy Environment

US energy policies also impact production and prices. For instance, a more environmentally focused administration may impose regulations and taxes that restrict production, raising prices. Conversely, policies encouraging production can alleviate supply constraints ([IG UK, 2018](https://www.ig.com/uk/news-and-trade-ideas/commodities-news/how-can-political-events-affect-the-oil-price--42098-180209)).

The Biden administration's ban on Russian oil imports and ongoing policy uncertainties have added to market volatility and supply challenges ([API, 2022](https://gaspricesexplained.com/)).

## Market Speculation and External Factors

Speculation in commodity markets can exacerbate price movements beyond what supply and demand fundamentals dictate.

- Reports indicate that unregulated speculation in global commodity markets may have contributed to unprecedented rises in natural gas prices during winter periods ([Essaytown, 2011](https://www.essaytown.com/subjects/paper/rising-gas-prices/49595)).
- External shocks such as hurricanes (e.g., Hurricane Ida) disrupt production and refining, temporarily reducing supply and pushing prices higher ([Market Realist, 2021](https://marketrealist.com/p/why-is-gas-so-expensive-right-now/)).

## Refining, Distribution, and Retail Factors

The cost of gasoline at the pump is influenced not only by crude oil prices but also by refining, distribution, marketing, and taxation.

- Crude oil accounts for approximately 61% of gasoline prices.
- Refining costs contribute about 14%, with distribution and marketing adding 11%.
- Federal and state taxes make up around 14% of the retail price ([Gas Prices Explained, 2022](https://gaspricesexplained.com/)).

Local factors such as competition, store location, and operational costs also affect retail prices.

## Summary of Key Causes of Rising Gas Prices

| Cause                         | Explanation                                                                                  | Effect on Gas Prices           |
|-------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------|
| Supply-Demand Imbalance        | Demand rebounding faster than supply growth; limited new supply                             | Primary driver of price increases |
| Geopolitical Instability       | Middle East conflicts, shipping route risks, OPEC production decisions                      | Creates supply uncertainty and price volatility |
| US Policy and Regulation       | Production restrictions, import bans, and policy uncertainty                               | Limits supply and raises prices |
| Market Speculation             | Unregulated trading and investor behavior                                                  | Amplifies price fluctuations  |
| Refining and Distribution Costs| Operational costs and taxes add to wholesale and retail prices                             | Contributes to final price at pump |

## Conclusion and Outlook

The rising cost of gas is a complex phenomenon driven predominantly by a persistent imbalance between supply and demand, exacerbated by geopolitical tensions, production constraints, and policy decisions. While demand is expected to grow moderately through 2025, supply is constrained by underinvestment, political risks, and regulatory environments, particularly in key producing regions such as the US shale sector and the Middle East.

Geopolitical instability and OPEC's cautious production policies further tighten supply, while market speculation and external shocks add volatility. Additionally, refining, distribution, and taxation contribute to the final price consumers pay.

Given these factors, it is reasonable to conclude that gas prices are likely to remain elevated in the near to medium term, with potential relief contingent on increased investment in production, geopolitical stabilization, and policy measures aimed at enhancing supply resilience. Policymakers focusing on incentivizing domestic production and energy infrastructure development may help mitigate price pressures.

